report.executive_summary: In a comprehensive tournament of 11 strategies over 121000 rounds, Grudger emerged as the dominant strategy with an average payoff of 2.54 per round. The tournament revealed that strategies balancing cooperation and defection based on reputation significantly outperform both naive cooperators and persistent defectors. With an overall cooperation rate of 55.4%, the results demonstrate that trust-based mechanisms can effectively promote mutual benefit even in competitive environments.

key_findings.title: Grudger Dominates Tournament
key_findings.description: Grudger achieved the highest average payoff of 2.54 per round, outperforming the second-place strategy by 0.9%.

key_findings.title: Cooperation Emerges Despite Competition
key_findings.description: Overall cooperation rate of 55.4% shows that mutual benefit strategies outperform pure exploitation.

recommendations: Organizations should consider implementing merit-based trust systems that combine forgiveness with accountability to maximize long-term cooperation.
